00:00:01.550 --> 00:00:05.200
&gt;&gt; John Boyd: All right. I'm John Boyd. It
is my great pleasure to introduce Professor

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:12.080
Kahneman today. And I just want to give you
a brief background on his outstanding career.

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:17.310
He started in 1954 received his bachelors
in experimental psychology and mathematics

00:00:17.310 --> 00:00:23.789
from the Hebrew University in Jerusalem. In
1961, he was awarded his Ph.D. from University

00:00:23.789 --> 00:00:31.050
of California Berkeley right across the bay
in Experimental Psychology. In 1979, he and

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:36.310
his coauthor Amos Tversky published their
seminal paper on Prospect Theory which started

00:00:36.310 --> 00:00:41.800
to change the way people reframed the argument
around gains, losses, and decision-making

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:47.219
under uncertainty. Several years later in
2002, Professor Kahneman was awarded the Nobel

00:00:47.219 --> 00:00:54.130
Prize largely on the work of Prospect Theory
of. And Nobel Prize isn't always impressive;

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:59.559
his perhaps more so because there isn't a
Nobel Prize in psychology. He had to win his

00:00:59.559 --> 00:01:05.550
Nobel Prize in economics. And as far as I
know, there's only one other person, one other

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:10.830
psychologist, who's won a Nobel Prize and
that's Ivan Pavlov. He may be a physiologist,

00:01:10.830 --> 00:01:16.940
we could argue about that. Years later, in
2007, Psychologist tried to reclaim Professor

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:21.710
Kahneman as one of their own when the American
Psychological Association awarded him Lifetime

00:01:21.710 --> 00:01:27.250
Distinguished Contribution Award. And today
he is a Senior Scholar at the Woodrow Wilson

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:31.640
School of Public and International Affairs
at Princeton University and he's here to talk

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:38.050
about his new book Thinking Fast and Slow.
Now Google's mission which we all know is

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:43.970
to take the world's information and to make
it more useful and universally accessible.

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:50.410
And all information, all knowledge, is important,
but I think some again is more important than

00:01:50.410 --> 00:01:54.630
others. Because the information that he'll
present today I think it's very personal;

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:59.740
it's about each of us. And, if you'll listen
carefully it's going to change the way you

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:04.340
think about yourself and the world around
you. So please join me in welcoming Professor

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:06.910
Kahneman to Google.

00:02:06.910 --> 00:02:08.910
[Applause]

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:23.900
&gt;&gt; Kahneman: Thank you. Well, I think intuition
has been discussed a lot in recent years and

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:30.370
I'll be talking about intuition. There are
two camps in this discussion naturally there

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:37.090
is the pro and the con. And of course, many
people here will have read Malcolm Gladwell

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:43.530
Blink which although it's not unconditional
defense of intuition, it certainly gave people

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:52.850
the impression that sometimes we magically
know things without knowing why we know them.

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:58.470
Within the discipline of psychology and the
decision making there is a group and it is

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:05.540
headed by a very interesting figure called
Gary Kline who wrote a book that I recommend.

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:12.260
Its Sources of Power is one of his books that
I would recommend the most warmly. And they

00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:22.460
are great believers in expert intuition. The
other side there are skeptics about intuition

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:28.010
in general and including expert intuition.
And I have long been counted as one of the

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:36.440
skeptics because my early work with Amos Tversky
was about intuitive errors and flaws and biases

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:43.860
of intuitive thinking. Today you find that
discussion in many places and for example

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:50.110
in medicine among the popular writers; two
writers both of whom write for the New Yorker,

00:03:50.110 --> 00:03:56.880
Jerome Groopman and Atul Gawande. They clearly
differ. Atul Gawande is in favor of formal

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:03.730
systems, very skeptical about human judgment
and wanting to prove all the time and Jerome

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:10.560
Groopman being in fact, although he doesn't
quite admit he really likes good old fashioned

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:17.400
medical intuition. Of course he likes physicians
well-educated. But he doesn't like formal

00:04:17.400 --> 00:04:24.130
system and the issue in medicine is "What
are the role of evidence based medicine and

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:32.680
how do you allocate that with 
the function of intuition?" The background

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:36.629
actually, part of the background for what
I'll talk about today is a strange collaboration

00:04:36.629 --> 00:04:41.599
in which I engaged with about eight years
with Gary Klein, whom I mentioned. He is a

00:04:41.599 --> 00:04:46.460
guru of a group of people who really, I wouldn't
say they despise what I do but they certainly

00:04:46.460 --> 00:04:53.259
don't like what I do because they think that
the emphasis and biases of judgment has drawn

00:04:53.259 --> 00:05:01.300
an unjustly unfavorable picture of the human
mind. And by and large I am inclined to agree.

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:06.259
Seven or eight years ago I invited him and
we worked together for a number of years trying

00:05:06.259 --> 00:05:12.560
to figure out where is the boundary? Where
is intuition marvelous and where is it flawed?

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:18.499
And I think we can tell. And we wrote a paper
at the end of six or seven years with a lot

00:05:18.499 --> 00:05:25.749
of vicissitudes that we went through since
we basically don't agree. We wrote a paper

00:05:25.749 --> 00:05:33.020
the title of which was A Failure to Disagree,
because on the substance I think we know and

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:38.569
we both agree where you can trust intuition
and where you cannot. Emotionally we haven't

00:05:38.569 --> 00:05:46.360
changed. He still hates the biases and doesn't
think that errors of experts are very funny

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:51.529
and I think that errors of experts are quite
funny [laughter] so that's a difference right

00:05:51.529 --> 00:06:00.090
there. There are two modes of thinking that
all of us are familiar with. And there is

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:06.939
one mode, one way for thoughts that come to
mind and listen to this. You know about this

00:06:06.939 --> 00:06:12.150
lady that she's I think adjust as quickly
as you know her hair is dark. And it's interesting

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:17.820
to dwell a bit about this. It is this is not
something that the judgment that she is angry,

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:23.039
the impression that she is angry. Doesn't
feel like something you did. It feels like

00:06:23.039 --> 00:06:29.619
something that happens. It happens to me.
We have the basic experience is a passive

00:06:29.619 --> 00:06:35.610
experience in those judgments. And that is
true of perception, when we see the world

00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:42.509
we don't decide to see it. It is true of impression.
And it is true in general what we call intuitive

00:06:42.509 --> 00:06:49.650
thinking. It just happens. It comes from somewhere.
And we are not the author of it. Now, there

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:56.649
is another way that thoughts come to mind
and here I suppose essentially nothing came

00:06:56.649 --> 00:07:05.740
to your mind, but the answer is 408. To produce
the 408, requires a completely different kind

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:11.610
of operation. You have to retrieve the program
that you learned in school. The program consists

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:16.979
of steps. You have to go through the steps.
You've got to pay attention successively to

00:07:16.979 --> 00:07:21.770
partial products and so on. And keep things
in mind and keep the whole program in mind.

00:07:21.770 --> 00:07:26.800
This is how it works. This is something that
you do. It is not something that happens to

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:37.919
you. And there are many indications that this
is how it works. One is that Physiology indicates

00:07:37.919 --> 00:07:42.629
and this is how it works: pupil dilates. This
is something that I studies many, many years

00:07:42.629 --> 00:07:47.629
ago that people really on a program like that
if you're on a problem like that if you're

00:07:47.629 --> 00:07:56.059
going to do it in your head, your pupil will
dilate. The area will increase by about 50%

00:07:56.059 --> 00:08:01.319
as soon as you engage in that. And it will
stay dilated as long as you're working and

00:08:01.319 --> 00:08:08.869
it will sort of collapse back to normal size
either when you quit or when you find the

00:08:08.869 --> 00:08:14.740
answer. So this is another way thoughts come
to mind. And this is definitely not the intuitive

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:21.149
way. Here we are we feel a sense of urgency.
We feel something deliberate is happening

00:08:21.149 --> 00:08:28.960
and a very important aspect of it this is
effortful and what psychologists mean by effort

00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:35.190
is basically, if you want the quick introduction
to what effort is, this is something you cannot

00:08:35.190 --> 00:08:41.229
do while making a left turn into traffic.
You cannot do it and you shouldn't try. And

00:08:41.229 --> 00:08:47.940
the reason is that there is limited capacity
to exert effort. And if you are engaged that

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:57.120
capacity or those resources at one task less
is available for another task. Now, there

00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:02.350
is another function of System 2. And here
I'm going to tell you a riddle. Most of you

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:09.790
are familiar with it. A bat and a ball together
costs 1.10. The bat costs more than the ball.

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:16.130
Of course how much does the ball cost? How
many people know this riddle by the way? Oh,

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:22.790
okay. So it's still usable. The point about
this riddle is that the number came to your

00:09:22.790 --> 00:09:30.990
mind. And the number is ten cents. And everybody
just, I think. Maybe here they're exception,

00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:35.690
very few exceptions. People confess that the
number ten cents immediately came to mind.

00:09:35.690 --> 00:09:44.579
Now, it's wrong. Ten cents and dollar 10 is
a dollar 20. The solution is five cents. What

00:09:44.579 --> 00:09:55.200
is interesting here is that at Princeton,
at MIT at Harvard and I don't know about Stanford

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:03.060
or CalTech about 50% of students asked this
question of undergraduates say ten cents.

00:10:03.060 --> 00:10:09.100
And we learn something very interesting when
somebody says ten cents. We learn that they

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:16.259
didn't check because if they had checked,
they wouldn't say ten cents. So, there is

00:10:16.259 --> 00:10:23.129
a sense of confidence that people have that
these people in particular have and it brings

00:10:23.129 --> 00:10:30.300
us to another function of what I'll call System
2. System 1 is the intuitive one; they perform

00:10:30.300 --> 00:10:40.709
those automatic and activities and System
2 is the effortful one the one that the deliberate

00:10:40.709 --> 00:10:48.140
one. And the reason that I classify this as
System 2 operation is that self-control and

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:55.870
controlling your attention and deliberate
exertion of effort are impaired when by other

00:10:55.870 --> 00:11:04.950
activities. So, if for example, a trivial
example, if somebody is asked to retain seven

00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:10.380
digits in their head and you then give them
a choice between chocolate cake, sinful chocolate

00:11:10.380 --> 00:11:15.480
cake and virtuous fruit salad they're more
likely to choose the chocolate cake than they

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:20.910
would if they didn't have seven digits in
their head. It takes effort to control your

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:31.730
impulses even such mild impulses as a preference
for chocolate cake. So 

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:37.519
you should be aware of that difference between
System 1 operations, the automatic ones and

00:11:37.519 --> 00:11:44.629
System 2 operations, the deliberate ones,
it comes very clearly when in driving. So

00:11:44.629 --> 00:11:51.790
driving is a skill. And any skilled activity
measure of skill is that things begin to happen

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:58.879
automatically. So you can drive and conduct
a conversation. You cannot make a left turn

00:11:58.879 --> 00:12:05.670
into traffic, but by and large, we can drive
and talk. So driving is largely automatic.

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:11.290
Braking, when there is any sign of danger,
braking is completely automatic. That is,

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:17.420
you can notice while you're braking, but you
first respond so that the response is immediate,

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:26.300
it is fully automatic. Now, in some places,
not here where people drive in snow or ice,

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:33.339
they learn about skids. And then, occasionally,
you'll find yourself as a driver in a skid.

00:12:33.339 --> 00:12:38.670
And then System 2 will be mobilized because
in a skid you're not supposed to do anything

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:43.860
that comes naturally to you. You shouldn't
brake and you shouldn't steer away from the

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:48.660
skid. You should leave the brakes alone and
steer into the skid, completely non-intuitive.

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:57.050
Now, when people have a lot of practice with
skids that too becomes automatic. So one thing

00:12:57.050 --> 00:13:03.510
that we can tell about System 1 and System
2 those two types of operations, is some of

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:11.170
the basic innate operations, functions that
we have such as having emotional reactions

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:19.779
to things, all this is System 1. We don't
choose to do it. It just happens to us. But

00:13:19.779 --> 00:13:28.089
also System 1 is where skill is. That is when
we get to be skilled at something it becomes

00:13:28.089 --> 00:13:34.370
automatic and it demands your resources and
we get to be very good at it. Now, the issue

00:13:34.370 --> 00:13:41.310
of intuition and here I'm not sure, but I
suspect that Malcolm Gladwell really did us

00:13:41.310 --> 00:13:46.459
a disservice by giving us a sense there is
magic to intuition. There really is no magic

00:13:46.459 --> 00:13:54.800
at all and we should understand how it works.
Intuition and Herbert Simon who was Psychologist

00:13:54.800 --> 00:14:00.130
then and economist and a political scientist
Nobel Laureate, Herbert Simon gave a very

00:14:00.130 --> 00:14:06.300
good definition about what intuition is. It
is simply recognition. There is really no

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:12.040
difference between the physician recognizing
a disease, you know, a particular disease

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:18.670
from a facial expression or something and
a little child learning, pointing to something

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:24.589
and saying doggie. The little child has no
idea what the clues are but he just said.

00:14:24.589 --> 00:14:33.000
He just knows this is dog without knowing
why he knows. And once you think about it

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:40.290
this way, this really demystifies intuition
to a very considerable extent. And it also

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:46.471
leads you to sort of a solution to the problem
Gary Klein and I were trying to solve. When

00:14:46.471 --> 00:14:53.580
can you trust intuition and when can't you?
And then it becomes an issue of is the world

00:14:53.580 --> 00:15:02.600
regular enough so that you can learn to recognize
things? Or and then did that particular individual

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:09.639
have an opportunity to learn the regularities
of the world? And so, the world of chess players

00:15:09.639 --> 00:15:14.670
is highly regular. And statistically, the
world of poker players is very regular. So

00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:22.300
there is an element of chance, but there are
rules and the mind is so set that if there

00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:28.470
are rules in the environment and we're exposed
to them for a long time, and we get immediate

00:15:28.470 --> 00:15:34.559
feedback on what is right and wrong, or fairly
immediate feedback, we would acquire those

00:15:34.559 --> 00:15:43.649
rules. So all of us have expert intuition
even if we are not physicians and we're not

00:15:43.649 --> 00:15:53.370
master chess players. I recognize my wife's
mood from one word on the telephone. You know,

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:58.779
most of you can do that. There's people that
you know very well. All of us recognize dangerous

00:15:58.779 --> 00:16:05.439
driver on the next lane. And you know we get
cues and we don't necessarily know what is

00:16:05.439 --> 00:16:11.520
the cue but this person is driving erratically
and could do something dangerous. And this

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:20.910
is a lot of reinforced practice and we're
very good at that. We can learn about those,

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:31.720
there are differences. Among experts, among
professionals, in the level of expertise that

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:37.639
they have and they depend in the level of
intuitive expertise that they can develop.

00:16:37.639 --> 00:16:43.649
So for example, compare anesthesiologists
to radiologists. Anesthesiologists get very

00:16:43.649 --> 00:16:49.100
good feedback, an immediate feedback whenever
they do anything wrong. You know they have

00:16:49.100 --> 00:16:57.439
those measurements in real time. Radiologists
get really miserable feedback about whether

00:16:57.439 --> 00:17:03.270
they're right or wrong. So you could expect
an anesthesiologist to develop intuition much

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:10.770
more than you would expect radiologist to
develop intuition. And so, that is part of

00:17:10.770 --> 00:17:18.130
the answer about intuitive expertise. We don't
need to disagree about that because we know

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:24.960
pretty much when intuitive expertise is likely
to develop. And as I said, we also that means

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:31.510
that intuitive expertise is not going to develop
in a chaotic universe or in a chaotic world.

00:17:31.510 --> 00:17:40.540
So for example, I personally do not believe
that that's stopped because people pick stocks

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:47.430
to invest in can develop intuition because
simply the market takes care of it. There

00:17:47.430 --> 00:17:53.380
isn't enough regularity in what's going to
happen to prices for intuitions to develop.

00:17:53.380 --> 00:18:00.030
We also know about political forecasters when
they forecast long-term, they are really no

00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:07.000
better than a dart-throwing monkey. And they
are certainly not better than the average

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:14.410
reader of the New York Times. Intuitions and
the reason it's not the pundit's fault. And

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:20.740
that research has been done with pundits and
CIA analysts and regional experts. It is really

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:26.770
not their fault that they cannot predict the
long range future 10 or 15 years. They are

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:31.820
quite good at short-term predictions. They
are really not good at all in long-term predictions.

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:38.550
It's not their fault. It's the fault of the
world. The world is probably not predictable.

00:18:38.550 --> 00:18:43.611
And if the world is not predictable, then
you are not going to predict it. When there

00:18:43.611 --> 00:18:50.750
are marginal situations where there is some
predictability but poor formulas do better

00:18:50.750 --> 00:18:58.700
than individuals. That is the domain where
formulas beat individuals regularly is a domain

00:18:58.700 --> 00:19:03.920
of fairly low predictability. Because when
there are weak cues, people are not very good

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:11.510
at picking them up and are not good at using
them consistently. But formulas can be generated

00:19:11.510 --> 00:19:19.060
on the basis of experience and they will do
a better job than individual judgment. Okay.

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:26.840
Now, I've introduced you to System 1 and System
2 and I've told you something about skill

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:39.890
and about skill in System 1. Now I'd like
to point out something that we sometimes have

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:47.411
intuitions and that applies to political forecasters
and to stock pickers and to all of us. Quite

00:19:47.411 --> 00:19:54.891
frequently we have intuitions that are false.
And they come up and come to mind and they

00:19:54.891 --> 00:20:01.880
are subjectively undistinguishable from expert
intuitions. So I'm now talking of people who

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:07.580
have intuitions that are not based on expertise.
And they come. They're System 1 in the sense

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:14.490
that they are effortless and automatic. And
where do they come from? And that is what

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:21.580
I'm going to try to illuminate, shed some
light on in the rest of the talk. So I want

00:20:21.580 --> 00:20:28.600
to introduce you to System 1. And first of
all, let me get one thing clear because I

00:20:28.600 --> 00:20:35.950
might forget. I use System 1 and System 2
those terms and very shocking terms in my

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:42.700
discipline. You are really not supposed to
do that. Because every psychologist gets told

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:48.400
fairly early you're not supposed to explain
what happens in the mind by invoking little

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:53.940
agents inside the mind and explain what the
mind does by what the little agents do. Those

00:20:53.940 --> 00:21:01.440
are homunculi and that's a bad word in psychology.
I'm going to use System 1 and System 2 absolutely

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:10.440
as homunculi. Now, what do I have to say in
my defense? First of all, well, I'm warning

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:14.640
you. Those are fictitious characters. They
don't exist. I don't believe there is such

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:19.250
a thing as System 1 and System 2. Don't look
for them in the brain, because they are not

00:21:19.250 --> 00:21:23.840
two systems in the brain of which one does
one and the other does the other. So why am

00:21:23.840 --> 00:21:30.020
I using this terrible language? I'm using
it because I think it's helpful. It fits the

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:35.900
way our minds work and to explain the background
of that decision of why I use System 1 and

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:48.090
System 2, I refer you to a very good book.
It's very entertaining. It's by Joshua Foer

00:21:48.090 --> 00:21:55.990
and it's called Moonwalking with Einstein.
It came out earlier this year. And what the

00:21:55.990 --> 00:22:02.790
book is about. Joshua Foer, he's a science
writer. And he went to the Memory Championship

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:07.460
of the United States. You might not know there
is such a thing but there is. So people memorize

00:22:07.460 --> 00:22:15.820
decks of cards and very, very long lists of
things and perform feats that we think are

00:22:15.820 --> 00:22:22.280
completely extraordinary. Joshua Foer decided
to find out what happens. And a year later

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:26.860
he was actually the champion -- the Memory
Champion of the United States. And the book

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:34.520
is a story of how he did it. And basically
the story which was known to the Greeks in

00:22:34.520 --> 00:22:41.800
some form is that memory is very, very good
at something and terrible at other things.

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:48.000
Memory is terrible at remembering lists. We're
really not good at remembering lists. Memory

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:56.880
is superb at remembering routes through space.
That evolution, evolution has endowed us with

