00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:12.810
fairly important, because what it means is,
you can think of well, let me add something.

00:28:12.810 --> 00:28:22.530
Then I'll pull it together. I think of System
1 very largely in terms of what happens in

00:28:22.530 --> 00:28:28.010
associative memory. To think of associative
memory, you can think of a gigantic network

00:28:28.010 --> 00:28:32.960
of ideas. And the ideas are linked to each
other in various way, associatively, some

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:41.560
of them are causes of other things or categories,
example, instances of. There are many different

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:50.350
links but you have a huge representation of
what we have in mind. And at any one time

00:28:50.350 --> 00:28:58.110
the stimulus occurs, it activates a subset
of those notes in that representation of memory

00:28:58.110 --> 00:29:05.370
and then activation spreads through the associative
network; not a lot, but it spreads some. So

00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:15.450
for example, you're now and we can know that
it spreads, because we become sensitized to

00:29:15.450 --> 00:29:22.320
other ideas that have been activated in this
fashion. So for example, right now, if somebody

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:28.760
whispered words in your ears, you would be
much more likely to detect and recognize words

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:36.840
like sickness and smell, instinct, and nausea,
and hangover. A lot of the associations have

00:29:36.840 --> 00:29:41.660
been activated. You're not aware of any of
them. You're not aware of anything. Those

00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:48.140
are not conscious activations. But they are
activations nonetheless. And because those

00:29:48.140 --> 00:29:55.110
ideas are partially activated, weak stimulus
is going to be sufficient to bring them over

00:29:55.110 --> 00:30:01.261
threshold. This again is a very important
function of System 1 associative memory. We

00:30:01.261 --> 00:30:09.820
are prepared basically by this spreading activation
prepares things for what might come next.

00:30:09.820 --> 00:30:20.140
You will be able to recognize and respond
to things more easily than before. Then something

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:32.160
else happens. And this is there are two words
here, banana vomit and you made a story. What

00:30:32.160 --> 00:30:38.700
happens, you know, there is really no need
to do that, but in effect, this was sufficient

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:45.101
to create a causal link so that somehow the
bananas caused the vomit. You didn't make

00:30:45.101 --> 00:30:51.410
a conscious decision for that to happen, but
we know that's the kind of thing that happens.

00:30:51.410 --> 00:30:58.390
As soon as a stimulus is presented, we look
back for causes; the associative machinery

00:30:58.390 --> 00:31:04.630
looks back and latches on possible causes.
Here it's very simple to find a cause and

00:31:04.630 --> 00:31:10.850
you know this has an effect. So temporarily,
you know, you don't like bananas because an

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:29.650
association has been created. And that happens
because of the causal surge. So [pause] this

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:41.570
should give you a sense of one of the functions
of System 1. And to complete that, let me

00:31:41.570 --> 00:31:48.090
show you something else. So this is a famous
psychological demonstration. Many of you might

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:55.240
not have seen it. You read that as A B C.
You read this as 12, 13, 14, but the B and

00:31:55.240 --> 00:32:01.320
the 13 are physically identical. So this tells
us something quite important about the way

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:10.880
that associative machinery in System 1 work
on new stimuli. Everything is made coherent.

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:17.130
So, in the context of letters, that ambiguous
stimulus is going to be read as a letter.

00:32:17.130 --> 00:32:22.700
In the context of numbers, it is going to
be read as a number. What is quite important,

00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:28.680
two aspects here, one is the coherence and
the other is that you are not aware of the

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:35.750
ambiguity. The ambiguity is suppressed. That
is, you just get one interpretation. In this

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:40.970
case, it's a coherent interpretation. And
that is the way that the system works. It

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:50.820
generates associatively coherent representations
of reaction to situation. Associative memory

00:32:50.820 --> 00:32:59.980
or System 1 is also very pository about world
knowledge. So when an event occurs, our reaction

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:05.970
to it is informed by a lot of things that
we know. And I'll give you my favorite example

00:33:05.970 --> 00:33:13.640
of this. This is people are listening to sentences
while events in their brain are recorded.

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:21.610
An upper class male British voice says, "I
have a large tattoo, I have large tattoos

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:28.830
all down my back." And approximately 3/10th
of a second later the brain responds with

00:33:28.830 --> 00:33:37.800
a characteristically surprise. This is astonishing
if you stop to think about it. There was that

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:43.380
voice. You have to classify it as an upper
class British voice. Now upper class British

00:33:43.380 --> 00:33:51.320
men don't have tattoos down their back, something
is odd and you get a surprised reaction. You

00:33:51.320 --> 00:33:57.810
get a mobilization of System 2 because System
2 is the one that pays attention. Surprise

00:33:57.810 --> 00:34:07.880
calls attention. A male voice saying I believe
I'm pregnant of course same thing. So this

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:15.100
system holds a world knowledge and uses a
world knowledge to classify situations as

00:34:15.100 --> 00:34:24.050
normal or abnormal and it does that at top
speed. And it updates very quickly. Well,

00:34:24.050 --> 00:34:34.390
I'll tell you a story about updating. It updates
what it considers normal. Now, this is an

00:34:34.390 --> 00:34:39.190
anecdote. You're free not to believe me. I
believe it because it's a personal experience.

00:34:39.190 --> 00:34:50.620
We were some years ago on vacation in Australia
in resort all of 40 little villas and in the

00:34:50.620 --> 00:34:55.830
evening we go to have dinner first evening
and we meet a psychologist from Stanford.

00:34:55.830 --> 00:35:03.070
Ah, surprise, coincidence and we are very
delighted to meet each other. Now, two weeks

00:35:03.070 --> 00:35:14.240
later, we're in the theater in London. And
it goes dark. And we watch. And then, the

00:35:14.240 --> 00:35:22.650
lights come back on and next to me, same guy.
Now, the important point is that I was less

00:35:22.650 --> 00:35:31.250
surprised the second time than the first.
Because "Oh, John, he is the guy I meet everywhere."

00:35:31.250 --> 00:35:35.360
[laughter]
It takes very little time to create what we

00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:43.780
call "a norm." So one event, the second event
links back to the first. If I had met anybody

00:35:43.780 --> 00:35:51.510
else, that is what's impressed me. If I had
met anybody else, I would have been more surprised.

00:35:51.510 --> 00:35:58.100
And that's odd if you think about statistically,
it's crazy. But in fact, it was very clear

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:04.200
that and I wouldn't say that I consciously
expect to see John wherever I go. But, you

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:09.160
know, if I'm going to meet someone, I'd be
prepared to meet John.

00:36:09.160 --> 00:36:13.850
[laughter]
Now, I've mentioned something about causal

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:20.551
thinking. And I want to give you some sense
how that works. So it's a question, which

00:36:20.551 --> 00:36:27.020
is more probable that a mother has blue eyes
if her daughter has blue eyes or her daughter

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:35.521
has blue eyes if her mother has blue eyes?
Now again, as in the bat and ball, there is

00:36:35.521 --> 00:36:40.890
an intuitive response and the intuitive response
is that it's more probable that a daughter

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:45.810
has blue eyes if her mother has blue eyes
than the other way around. If you stop to

00:36:45.810 --> 00:36:51.060
do the math on the assumption that the incidence
of blue eyes is the same two generations the

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:58.670
probabilities are strictly equal but even
before you do the math, your reasoning flows

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:05.931
along causal lines. Your thinking flows along
causal lines. This happens intuitively. One

00:37:05.931 --> 00:37:13.710
of these feels okay. It feels more coherent
and the coherence that we experience can be

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:19.870
turned into a judgment of probability. That
is, the confidence that we experience is a

00:37:19.870 --> 00:37:34.090
judgment of probability. Now, I'm going to
skip the other example. And I said earlier

00:37:34.090 --> 00:37:42.230
that people have intuitions that are not necessarily
true. And that people are confident in judgments

00:37:42.230 --> 00:37:50.900
that are not necessarily true. And I would
like to sort of present a tentative theory

00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:58.780
about how that happened. And the general idea
is very straightforward. When we're asked

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:06.700
a question that we cannot answer, typically
System 1 is going to come up with the answer

00:38:06.700 --> 00:38:12.310
to a related question that is easier. And
it's going to use that answer to the wrong

00:38:12.310 --> 00:38:19.870
question, the question that hasn't been asked
in place of the question that was asked. We

00:38:19.870 --> 00:38:25.890
call that a mechanism of substitution: substituting
an easier question for a hard one. It happens

00:38:25.890 --> 00:38:31.620
automatically. People are not aware that it
happens and it is a source of many intuitions

00:38:31.620 --> 00:38:37.330
that don't come from expertise and they are
much less likely to be correct than the intuitions

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:43.570
that do come from expertise but they come
with equal confidence just about. So there

00:38:43.570 --> 00:38:48.180
are several mechanisms that take part in this
substitution thing and I'd like to introduce

00:38:48.180 --> 00:38:55.800
them. One of them which I call the mental
shotgun is that when you are instructed to

00:38:55.800 --> 00:39:01.470
perform an operation, you typically perform
other operations as well that are related

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:08.230
to it associatively, are related to the target
operation, but they are different. My favorite

00:39:08.230 --> 00:39:14.520
example is, I'll say words and you are to
judge as quickly as possible whether the words

00:39:14.520 --> 00:39:20.560
rhyme or not. And the first pair of words
is vote note. That's easy. The second pair

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:28.441
of questions is vote goat. And vote goat is
substantially harder than vote no. Why? Although

00:39:28.441 --> 00:39:36.190
nobody else asked you to, you spelled. And
vote goat, there is a mismatch in spelling.

00:39:36.190 --> 00:39:41.930
Although they rhyme at least as I pronounce
them just as well as vote note, you have a

00:39:41.930 --> 00:39:49.040
conflict and the conflict slows you down.
So typically, we compute more than we intend

00:39:49.040 --> 00:40:02.231
to compute. And we can and that allows for
substitutions to take place. So let me give

00:40:02.231 --> 00:40:10.231
you an example of the substitution here. The
question here would be, "Which of the three

00:40:10.231 --> 00:40:23.100
figures is larger on the screen?" And the
answer is, "they're equal." All three figures

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:30.120
on the screen are of equal size. But it's
a very powerful illusion. We see the figure

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:36.640
on the right as larger than the figure out
left. And we see it because we can't help

00:40:36.640 --> 00:40:43.020
it. Although you were told to think of it
as a two-dimensional object, you compute the

00:40:43.020 --> 00:40:47.850
three-dimensional solution in which the object
on the right is in fact larger than the object

00:40:47.850 --> 00:40:55.000
on the left and that is what you see. There
are many other examples of this general process.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:41:04.360
Another one I like is called the dating heuristic.
Students are asked in a survey they're asked

00:41:04.360 --> 00:41:08.610
a couple of questions. How happy are you and
the other is how many dates did you have last

00:41:08.610 --> 00:41:16.480
month? And if you ask the questions in that
order, the correlation is essentially zero.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:22.440
Turns out there are many things in life that
determine happiness and dating is not particularly

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:27.290
important. You invert the order. So you ask
people, "How many dates did you have last

00:41:27.290 --> 00:41:32.920
month and how happy are you with your life
as a whole?" Correlation is .66.

00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:38.630
[laughter]
What has happened and this is both a heuristic

00:41:38.630 --> 00:41:45.520
and example what I call a focus and an illusion.
That you have an emotional reaction to the

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:50.480
student has an emotional reaction to the question
about the number of dates. That emotional

00:41:50.480 --> 00:41:55.930
reaction is sitting there. Then you're asked
the related question about happiness and without

00:41:55.930 --> 00:42:01.021
knowing that you are doing this, you substitute
one for the other. And you can do it for many

00:42:01.021 --> 00:42:07.580
questions. Now, it's not that people are confused
what happiness is. They know happiness is

00:42:07.580 --> 00:42:13.220
not satisfaction with the number of dates.
It's just that this is the answer that comes

00:42:13.220 --> 00:42:20.830
to mind to the happiness question. There has
been substitution and you are not aware of

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:29.350
it. Now, there is a process that is essential
to this and this is another strange ability

00:42:29.350 --> 00:42:38.040
of System 1. We can map intensities across
different dimensions. So I'll give you my

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:44.730
standard example for this. It's about Julie
who is a graduating senior and she read fluently

00:42:44.730 --> 00:42:53.330
when she was age 4 and the question is what
is her GPA? And the odd thing is that you

00:42:53.330 --> 00:42:57.810
know what her GPA is pretty much. At least
you have an idea. I mean, it's clearly about

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:05.420
3.2. It's clearly less than 4 about 3.7 maybe
which is ridiculous of course. But how do

00:43:05.420 --> 00:43:14.180
people get to 3.7 or somewhere like that?
Well, here is how it goes. She read fluently

00:43:14.180 --> 00:43:23.270
at age 4. That gives us an impression of precocity.
How precocious was she as a reader? And that

00:43:23.270 --> 00:43:28.190
people could express that in percentiles.
What is the likelihood that you could meet

00:43:28.190 --> 00:43:32.940
a child who would read faster than that? Then
when you are asked a question about what is

00:43:32.940 --> 00:43:40.190
her GPA? Without your knowing it, you are
matching the percentiles and you get the GPA

00:43:40.190 --> 00:43:46.550
that is about as extreme in the distribution
of GPA as reading at age 4 is in the distribution

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:54.800
of reading age. Completely unaware. Statistically,
completely absurd. You should be much more

00:43:54.800 --> 00:44:02.310
regressive. This is not the correct answer.
But this is a compelling subjective answer.

00:44:02.310 --> 00:44:09.420
This is one of the mechanisms that leads to
intuitive errors this mechanism of substitution.

00:44:09.420 --> 00:44:16.900
And I'll give you one more example. International
travels, this is an experiment. The experiment

00:44:16.900 --> 00:44:22.950
was run during a period when there were many
terrorist incidents in Europe. So that's a

00:44:22.950 --> 00:44:27.260
background. How much will you pay for insurance
that pays 100,000 dollars in case of death

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:33.750
for any reason? And how much would you pay
for insurance that pays 100,000 dollars in

00:44:33.750 --> 00:44:39.380
case of a death in a terror incident? People
pay much more for the second than for the

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:40.890
first.
[laughter]

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:47.070
And the reason that they do is that there
is an immediate response which is how afraid

00:44:47.070 --> 00:44:53.660
am I? And I am more afraid, most people are,
I'm more afraid of the idea of dying in a

00:44:53.660 --> 00:44:59.430
terrorist incident than they are afraid of
dying. And that is the mapping that takes

00:44:59.430 --> 00:45:07.090
place. Again, you know, it's that's the way
it works. This is the associative machinery.

00:45:07.090 --> 00:45:13.430
And when beautiful thing about it it doesn't
get stumped. It produces an answer to questions

00:45:13.430 --> 00:45:19.360
that it doesn't know how to answer. But it
produces them by answering easier questions

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:33.250
and a lot of our mental life is conducted
in just this way. So let me complete the circle

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:43.030
and talk a little bit about subjective confidence.
Subjective confidence, which is closely related

00:45:43.030 --> 00:45:50.100
to the probability of being correct, is actually
not a judgment at all. It is a feeling. It

00:45:50.100 --> 00:45:56.220
is a feeling that people have. And I think
we know where the origin of that feeling is.

00:45:56.220 --> 00:46:03.950
And it is System 1 if you will assessing the
fluency of its own processing; assessing the

00:46:03.950 --> 00:46:10.750
coherence of the story it has created to deal
with the current situation. And if the story

00:46:10.750 --> 00:46:17.560
is coherent, confidence is high. Now, this
is disastrous in some ways, because you can

00:46:17.560 --> 00:46:23.420
make a very coherent story out of very little
information and out of information that is

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:29.640
in fact not reliable. The quality of the story
depends very little on the quality and quantity

00:46:29.640 --> 00:46:38.060
of the information so people can be very confident
with very little reason. Confidence is therefore

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:45.721
not a good diagnostic for when you can trust
either yourself or somebody else. And if you

00:46:45.721 --> 00:46:50.550
are to evaluate whether you can trust somebody
who has a lot of confidence, that's not the

00:46:50.550 --> 00:46:57.900
way to do it. The way to do it as I'm saying
earlier is to ask what environment have they

00:46:57.900 --> 00:47:03.330
been in? And have they had an opportunity
to learn its regularities? Subjective confidence

00:47:03.330 --> 00:47:15.090
is not a good indicator. So that's, you know,
the story I could tell in about 45 minutes

00:47:15.090 --> 00:47:21.890
about the two systems. So let me remind you
they don't exist. But I think you should feel

00:47:21.890 --> 00:47:28.460
free to think in those terms, because what
you may be beginning to do is, you may be

00:47:28.460 --> 00:47:34.820
beginning to have an idea of the personality
of System 1 and System 2. Now this is ridiculous,

00:47:34.820 --> 00:47:41.150
but having an idea of those personalities
will actually enable you to think better about

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:48.090
psychological events than if you were just
had a long list of unrelated phenomena. So

00:47:48.090 --> 00:47:53.120
those ideas, those personalities, have a certain
coherence. And, you know, they're worth something

00:47:53.120 --> 00:48:05.330
in the coin of being able to make judgments.
Okay. I think we should open for questions.

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:06.330
So.

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:07.330
[Applause].

00:48:07.330 --> 00:48:22.260
&gt;&gt; John: We have the mic up there and I also
have hand-held mics if somebody has questions.

00:48:22.260 --> 00:48:27.500
Somebody's got to ask the first question.

00:48:27.500 --> 00:48:35.200
&gt;&gt; Male # 1: Hey. How fixed or plastic are
the System 1 processes? And are there thing

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:40.030
like mindfulness or emotional regulation that
have any effect?

00:48:40.030 --> 00:48:48.700
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: As I have described it, System
1 can be updated in terms of content very

00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:54.710
regularly. So you can learn in one trial what
is normal and what is not normal. What is

00:48:54.710 --> 00:49:05.200
very difficult to do is to get control over
how it works, over the rules of its operation.

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:14.010
And so, I do not know of a lot of evidence
that people, that System 1 can change unless

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:20.260
you have a quiet skill which requires reinforced
practice. What you can do and what people

00:49:20.260 --> 00:49:28.680
clearly can do is you can educate your System
2. And you can educate and you can learn to

00:49:28.680 --> 00:49:37.210
recognize situations in which System 2 takes
over and takes control of the reaction thereby

00:49:37.210 --> 00:49:43.050
avoid some mistakes. Can't be done too much.
But if I don't sound optimistic about training

00:49:43.050 --> 00:49:46.710
System 1, it's because I'm not.

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:53.660
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Another question about training
System 1. You talked about reinforcement learning

00:49:53.660 --> 00:50:00.000
and the time constants and the immediacy in
building expertise, but many of the practices

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:05.730
we have around building software development,
the time constants are somewhat longer and

00:50:05.730 --> 00:50:12.410
in particular you gave a counterexample which
was your Australia/UK visit and the fact that

00:50:12.410 --> 00:50:21.290
a single incident with John predisposed you
to that association. And so, I wonder if there

00:50:21.290 --> 00:50:28.400
has there been any testing to see what time
constants really play a role here?

00:50:28.400 --> 00:50:33.240
&gt;&gt; Kahneman: No. In terms of updating and
learning associations, this is something we

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:40.170
can learn quite quickly. You can be taught
to be afraid of something without anything

00:50:40.170 --> 00:50:49.750
else happening. And so, in that sense, System
1 associative memory can be updated. And you

00:50:49.750 --> 00:50:56.760
can now be developing software expertise that
is a somewhat different story and it's more

00:50:56.760 --> 00:51:04.859
like learning how to be a chess master. And
that takes a lot of experience. So that you

00:51:04.859 --> 00:51:11.250
and a lot of reinforcement and it had better
be effective reinforcement. Now, in the software

00:51:11.250 --> 00:51:17.030
thing, the time is to some extent not a big
problem. Because ultimately you are going

00:51:17.030 --> 00:51:22.720
to see it all together: the error you made
and the correct solutions. So time is not

00:51:22.720 --> 00:51:32.410
major factor. In learning, you know, how to
not steer a tanker, that's reinforcement is

00:51:32.410 --> 00:51:39.590
very slow. And it's a lot harder to learn
to do that than it is to learn to steer a

00:51:39.590 --> 00:51:40.590
smaller ship.

00:51:40.590 --> 00:51:44.961
&gt;&gt; Male #3: So this is a pretty broad question
so please take this whichever direction you

00:51:44.961 --> 00:51:49.860
like. But I was just wondering how these systems
come into play and how you see it in media

00:51:49.860 --> 00:51:56.030
and advertising and maybe I was thinking of
how it's changed over time.

00:51:56.030 --> 00:52:02.660
&gt;&gt; Kahneman: Well, it's very clear that advertising
is here to address System 1. It doesn't convey

00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:08.760
information for judgments. It moves your emotions
and it creates associations. That's what it

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:18.730
is intended to do and it's pretty effective.
So, a lot of politics is addressed to System

00:52:18.730 --> 00:52:26.710
1, a lot of political messaging. The influences
of System 1 activities and you know which

00:52:26.710 --> 00:52:33.000
are really important and we should be thinking
about. It's pretty frightening. One of my

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:38.720
colleagues at Princeton, my younger colleagues
at Princeton, has done studies on the effects

00:52:38.720 --> 00:52:49.010
of facial characteristics on political preferences.
And it's utterly amazing. You take 538 pairs

00:52:49.010 --> 00:52:56.590
of pictures of the two contestants for each
Congressional race and you show those pairs

00:52:56.590 --> 00:53:01.760
of pictures to Princeton students for 1/10th
of a second and you ask, "Which looks more

00:53:01.760 --> 00:53:10.370
competent?" That predicts 70% of elections.
So the impact of System 1 on the decisions

00:53:10.370 --> 00:53:15.640
we make for example, how much to pay in an
honesty box, that is something that we're

00:53:15.640 --> 00:53:20.190
really very rarely aware of and it's much
more than we think.

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:26.940
&gt;&gt; Male #4: So in, although that you say System
1 and System 2 don't show up as specific structures,

00:53:26.940 --> 00:53:32.950
have there been functional MRI, diffusion-spectral
imaging, diffusion-tensoral imaging studies

00:53:32.950 --> 00:53:40.340
that highlight whether System 1 is more primal
brain initial activation and System 2 is more

00:53:40.340 --> 00:53:41.340
neocortex?

00:53:41.340 --> 00:53:53.480
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: Well, you know, System 1 is extremely
sophisticated. So it's not, that is in part

00:53:53.480 --> 00:53:59.940
why I don't believe there is any simple representation
in the brain of those two systems because

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:06.720
what I've called System 1 operation by their
characteristics include both innate responses

00:54:06.720 --> 00:54:14.640
and highly skilled responses. And the whole
the representation of world knowledge is in

00:54:14.640 --> 00:54:22.010
System 1. So it's hard to classify one as
primitive. And I should add that System 2,

00:54:22.010 --> 00:54:29.260
the reasoning system as it were is not necessarily
rational. I mean, System 2 knows what it knows.

00:54:29.260 --> 00:54:36.890
It knows what we know and we don't know a
lot. So it's not that System 2 is infallible

00:54:36.890 --> 00:54:42.000
and that all the mistakes come from System
1. We make very significant mistakes when

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.860
we think very seriously. Yes.

00:54:44.860 --> 00:54:51.680
&gt;&gt; Male #3: So you mention that experts when
making long-term forecasts and they trust

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:56.780
their intuition they're often wrong. But there
are still a lot of people who listen to them.

00:54:56.780 --> 00:55:02.740
So, is it bad for the society in general that
we listen to experts who may be just as wrong

00:55:02.740 --> 00:55:08.560
as we are and should we be worried? Should
we try to do something?

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:15.800
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: I think there is a very good reason
for the demand for experts. I was referring

00:55:15.800 --> 00:55:21.640
to a particular book that you may want to
read or you may want to look for the New Yorker

00:55:21.640 --> 00:55:28.070
review of that book. It's a book by Phil Tetlock
on political judgment where he studied forecasts

00:55:28.070 --> 00:55:34.690
in the time range of 10, 15 years of political
forecasts. And one of the interesting observations

00:55:34.690 --> 00:55:39.920
is who are the people we like to listen to
as pundits? And there are people with very

00:55:39.920 --> 00:55:45.260
high confidence who think they understand
the world. Now, they actually are worse than

00:55:45.260 --> 00:55:51.191
chance. I mean, they are worse than people
who are more hesitant. But we want them. We

00:55:51.191 --> 00:55:58.150
need them. And so, there is a real demand
for overconfidence. [laughter]

00:55:58.150 --> 00:56:05.280
&gt;&gt; Male #5: So as you were going through all
the slides of the various illusions, by the

00:56:05.280 --> 00:56:10.300
time you came to the three figures on the
screen, I guess I was expecting there was

00:56:10.300 --> 00:56:16.310
something. So even though the lot on the right
looked bigger, I looked again okay and they're

00:56:16.310 --> 00:56:18.720
the same. So was that System 1 or System 2.

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:25.030
&gt;&gt; Kahneman: That is clearly System 2. And
that is the way we can learn to overcome illusions

00:56:25.030 --> 00:56:34.099
both visual and cognitive. You still see it
as one larger than the other, but you know

00:56:34.099 --> 00:56:40.390
that when you see a display like that, you
shouldn't trust your eyes. And to a similar

00:56:40.390 --> 00:56:46.480
extent you can recognize that you're in a
situation where somebody is having too much

00:56:46.480 --> 00:56:54.410
effect on you because she's very eloquent.
But you know the content may not be there.

00:56:54.410 --> 00:56:56.800
And so, you force yourself to be skeptical.

00:56:56.800 --> 00:57:02.480
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Is there any research to that effect
that people would avail that advertising is

00:57:02.480 --> 00:57:06.430
going to have an emotional effect on them?
Is there any res- let me say that I'm aware

00:57:06.430 --> 00:57:11.520
that advertising is supposed to have an emotional
effect on me activate System 1, will I be

00:57:11.520 --> 00:57:14.609
better suited to sort of ignore those things?

00:57:14.609 --> 00:57:19.970
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: I mean you certainly are going
to ignore it better than if you didn't know

00:57:19.970 --> 00:57:27.800
it whether you're capable of ignoring it altogether,
that I'm much more skeptical about. The real

00:57:27.800 --> 00:57:33.970
thing is not to expose yourself to it. Because
once you're exposed to it, it's going to affect

00:57:33.970 --> 00:57:43.180
you. And you know, those effects are the cues
in our world that we are not aware of can

00:57:43.180 --> 00:57:48.290
be extremely powerful. There is a whole line
of study, it's not exactly to your point,

00:57:48.290 --> 00:57:53.359
but I must tell you that story. There is a
whole line of studies on what happens to people

00:57:53.359 --> 00:57:59.680
when they're exposed to the idea of money.
And for example, they perform one task and

00:57:59.680 --> 00:58:04.990
there is a computer nearby and on the computer
there is a screensaver and the screensaver

00:58:04.990 --> 00:58:11.040
are dollars floating in water. Dollar bills
floating in water. That makes you selfish.

00:58:11.040 --> 00:58:17.770
It makes you reluctant to ask for the help
of others. It makes you put your chair further

00:58:17.770 --> 00:58:23.090
away from the chairs of other people when
you have to set up an interview situation.

00:58:23.090 --> 00:58:28.869
It has effects on all sorts of behaviors that
people are completely unaware of. And the

00:58:28.869 --> 00:58:36.490
links are symbolic. And you can be aware of
that. How can you resist it? We are exposed

00:58:36.490 --> 00:58:42.100
to money and it's going to have some effect.
Now, if you're designing an organization or

00:58:42.100 --> 00:58:47.280
if you're designing an environment for people,
you can create an environment that will remind

00:58:47.280 --> 00:58:51.980
people of money all the time or you can create
an environment that will remind them of other

00:58:51.980 --> 00:58:56.620
things and that will control their behavior
to some extent.

00:58:56.620 --> 00:59:01.910
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Although possibly not one of the
big five in the personality trait categories

00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:08.180
yet, have you developed any empirical testing
that ranks people on a scale of one-to-two

00:59:08.180 --> 00:59:12.499
and shows where they fall in terms of default
behaviors.

00:59:12.499 --> 00:59:20.730
&gt;&gt; Kahneman: Well, there is a relevant scale
on the activity of System 2. And the bat and

00:59:20.730 --> 00:59:26.950
ball question is actually a very, very good
question. There are several examples of this.

00:59:26.950 --> 00:59:33.130
My former colleague Shane Frederick developed
that test. It's called the Cognitive Reflection

00:59:33.130 --> 00:59:40.600
Test and the people who fail that item that
is, who say ten cents they are different in

00:59:40.600 --> 00:59:45.710
some interesting ways from the people who
are better able to make it. And let me give

00:59:45.710 --> 00:59:52.290
you an example. You ask them, you know, standard
Amazon questions. So you ordered a gift for

00:59:52.290 --> 00:59:56.910
yourself. How much will you pay extra to have
it tomorrow rather than the second business

00:59:56.910 --> 01:00:02.099
day? And the people who fail this item are
willing to pay more to get it tomorrow. So

01:00:02.099 --> 01:00:11.369
there are connections. What there isn't and
I'm very surprised there isn't, I don't know

01:00:11.369 --> 01:00:17.320
there should be tests of intelligence that
are tests of System 1. That are tests of the

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:22.910
richness and subtlety of the model of the
world that we have. All the intelligence tests

01:00:22.910 --> 01:00:28.609
that we have are tests for System 2. They're
reasoning tests. We don't have and I wish

01:00:28.609 --> 01:00:33.280
somebody would develop it and I hope somebody
will but, in fact, we don't have it.

01:00:33.280 --> 01:00:40.119
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Hi. So this is sort of a 2-part
question. So do you find that people who are

01:00:40.119 --> 01:00:47.230
more System 1 or System 2 prone for immediate
judgments are more likely to be that way long-term

01:00:47.230 --> 01:00:49.400
like larger decisions?

01:00:49.400 --> 01:00:52.580
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: I don't know enough about this.

01:00:52.580 --> 01:00:53.580
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Yeah.

01:00:53.580 --> 01:00:59.960
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: We do know that self-control and
the general activation of System 2 is an important

01:00:59.960 --> 01:01:06.070
personality characteristic. And you know its
presence in a rudimentary form at age four

01:01:06.070 --> 01:01:14.490
and has implications. The ability the test
is called The Marshmallow Test. You ask a

01:01:14.490 --> 01:01:20.961
child you can have one marshmallow now or
you can have two if you wait 15 minutes. That

01:01:20.961 --> 01:01:27.550
predicts what they will do 20 years later
remarkably well so there are things that are

01:01:27.550 --> 01:01:28.550
quite stable.

01:01:28.550 --> 01:01:32.780
&gt;&gt; Male #6: And the other part is that have
you encountered people who would say they

01:01:32.780 --> 01:01:37.359
have to make a decision and they're aware
that their System 1 mind is telling them decision

01:01:37.359 --> 01:01:43.630
A their System 2 mind is telling them decision
B. What do people go with?

01:01:43.630 --> 01:01:46.680
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: I don't know enough.

01:01:46.680 --> 01:01:49.300
&gt;&gt;Male #6: No?

01:01:49.300 --> 01:01:55.330
&gt;&gt;Kahneman: No, I don't know enough. [pause]
No, I don't know enough. It would be so dependent

01:01:55.330 --> 01:02:05.460
on circumstance whether you impose the System
2 judgment. In many cases, really System 2

01:02:05.460 --> 01:02:11.740
just endorses what System 1 subjects to. That's
the model you have. Sometimes you can overturn

01:02:11.740 --> 01:02:16.070
it. It's hard work.

01:02:16.070 --> 01:02:17.150
[pause]

01:02:17.150 --> 01:02:19.310
Thank you.

01:02:19.310 --> 01:02:20.400
[Applause]

